07595nam a22008055i 9780822382317DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223823177 a10.1515/97808223823172doi  a(DE-B1597)553849  a(OCoLC)1226680220  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHC59.72.C3bP65 1997 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04aThe Politics of Culture in the Shadow of Capital /cLisa Lowe, Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish, David Lloyd. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (604 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. CRITIQUE OF MODERNITY -- tThe Time of History and the Times of Gods -- tThe Gender and Labor Politics of Postmodernity -- tOutlines of a Nonlinear Emplotment of Philippine History -- tDevelopmentalism's Irresistible Seduction - Rural Subjectivity under Sandinista Agricultural Policy -- tNationalisms against the State -- tII. ALTERNATIVES -- tCultural Politics and Biological Diversity: State, Capital, and Social Movements in the Pacific Coast of Colombia -- tFirst Stop, Port-au-Prince: Mapping Postcolonial Africa through Toussaint L'Ouverture and His Black Jacobins -- tThe Veil in Their Minds and on Our Heads: Veiling Practices and Muslim Women -- tOutlaw Language: Creating Alternative Public Spheres in Basque Free Radio -- tIII. "UNLIKELY COALITIONS" -- tAngela Davis: Reflections on Race, Class, and Gender in the USA -- t"Frantic to Join ... the Japanese Army": The Asia Pacific War in the Lives of African American Soldiers and Civilians -- tWork, Immigration, Gender: New Subjects of Cultural Politics -- tWomen Who Walk on Water: Working across "Race" in Women Against Fundamentalism -- tIV. WORLD CULTURE AND PRACTICE -- tOf Zapatismo: Reflections on the Folkloric and the Impossible in a Subaltern Insurrection -- tStaging Resistance: The Indian People's Theatre Association -- tThe Discourse of Decolonization and Popular Memory: South Korea -- tIn the Shadows of Stonewall: Examining Gay Transnational Politics and the Diasporic Dilemma -- tWoman at the Close of the Maoist Era in the Polemics of Li Xiaojiang and Her Associates -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlobal in scope, but refusing a familiar totalizing theoretical framework, the essays in The Politics of Culture in the Shadow of Capital demonstrate how localized and resistant social practices-including anticolonial and feminist struggles, peasant revolts, labor organizing, and various cultural movements-challenge contemporary capitalism as a highly differentiated mode of production.Reworking Marxist critique, these essays on Asia, Latin America, the Caribbean, North America, and Europe advance a new understanding of "cultural politics" within the context of transnational neocolonial capitalism. This perspective contributes to an overall critique of traditional approaches to modernity, development, and linear liberal narratives of culture, history, and democratic institutions. It also frames a set of alternative social practices that allows for connections to be made between feminist politics among immigrant women in Britain, women of color in the United States, and Muslim women in Iran, Egypt, Pakistan, and Canada; the work of subaltern studies in India, the Philippines, and Mexico; and antiracist social movements in North and South America, the Caribbean, and Europe. These connections displace modes of opposition traditionally defined in relation to the modern state and enable a rethinking of political practice in the era of global capitalism.Contributors. Tani E. Barlow, Nandi Bhatia, Dipesh Chakrabarty, Chungmoo Choi, Clara Connolly, Angela Davis, Arturo Escobar, Grant Farred, Homa Hoodfar,